definition.value: Overlapping discrimination based on multiple aspects of a person's identity or group membership.
Donation of both an oocyte and sperm.
A partial gender identity in which individuals part(s) of one's gender fluctuate in intensity, while others remain static.
Artificial insemination performed outside of a clinical environment.

A subtle form of dehumanization in which fiction literature is used to teach history in schools; for instance, using literature which is said to be "age-appropriate" in order to propagate a less horrific version of historical events, or to otherwise position others living through those atrocities as "historically innocent".

Named after the book The Boy in the Striped Pajamas, by John Boyne, following the banning of the book Maus by the McMinn County, Tennessee, Board of Education. Autho Gwen C. Katz noted that "[t]he Boy in the Striped Pajamas is tailor-made for classroom use. It's taught at countless schools and it's squeaky-clean of any of the parent-objectionable material you might find in Maus, Night, or any of the other first-person accounts of the Holocaust... It's also a terrible way to teach the Holocaust." Katz goes on to state several historical issues with the portrayal set forward in The Boy in the Striped Pajamas, saying "The Boy in the Striped Pajamas turns a specific historical atrocity into a parable about all forms of bigotry and injustice. I'm sure Boyne thinks he's being very profound. But the actual effect is to blunt and erase the atrocity."
Padding or a phallic object which is worn in order to give the appearance of a penis, or to give the appearance of a larger penis.
A United States organization for gay and gay-friendly evangelicals, founded by Ralph Blair in 1975.
A document section of a book within a Bible.
A short piece of text.

Formally, a single metrical line in a poetic composition. However, verse has come to represent any division or grouping of words in a poetic composition, with groupings traditionally having been referred to as stanzas.
A short piece of text which forms part of a Biblical chapter.
Any of various Biblical verses about, interpreted as being about, or otherwise said to pertain to, LGBTQIA+ persons.

A rape law in a jurisdiction under which a man who commits rape, sexual assault, statutory rape, abduction or other similar act is exonerated if he marries his female victim, or in some jurisdictions at least offers to marry her. The "marry-your-rapist" law is a legal way for the accused to avoid prosecution or punishment.
Genocide against LGBTQIA+ persons.
Genocide against transgender persons.
Genocide against gay persons.
A thin sheet of plastic or latex used during oral intercourse to prevent transmission of sexually transmitted infections.

An interdisciplinary academic field that uses performance as a lens and a tool to study the world. The term performance is broad, and can include artistic and aesthetic performances like concerts, theatrical events, and performance art; sporting events; social, political and religious events like rituals, ceremonies, proclamations and public decisions; certain kinds of language use; and those components of identity which require someone to do, rather than just be, something.
Any of various theoryes which seek to define the heuristic concept of culture in operational and/or scientific terms.
Broadly, any of various theories related to the phenomenon of performance.

A performance theory formulated in the 1990s by Judith Butler, arguing that human beings create gender through repeated expression and performance of gender signifiers, limited by cultural expectations, limitations, and roles.
The idea that people learn about, or perceive the world by constructing mental models.

A theory of knowledge according to which human beings rationalize their experience by creating a model of the social world and how it functions, and language is the most essential system through which humans construct reality.

A theory in feminism and sociology about the manifestation of cultural origins, mechanisms, and corollaries of gender perception and expression in the context of interpersonal and group social interaction. Specifically, the social construction of gender stipulates that gender roles are an achieved "status" in a social environment, which implicitly and explicitly categorize people and therefore motivate social behaviors.
A sex party built around safer sex practices, or otherwise centering safer sex practices.
A sex party involving sex between multiple participants simultaneously.
A series of two or more killings, committed as separate events, usually, but not always, by one offender acting alone.
Status of a given biomarker, an objective indicator of a medical state observer from outside of the patient themselves.
The presence or absence of a serological marker in the blood.
The presence or absence of a serological HIV marker in the blood.
Disclosure of an individual's serostatus.
Disclosure of an individual's HIV serostatus.
A serostatus in which an individual has detectable levels of an HIV marker within the serum.
A serostatus in which an individual has no detectable level of an HIV marker within the serum.
Any of various legislation related to LGBTQIA+ persons, causes, culture, or rights.
Any of various legislation related to same-gender unions and marriages.
Legislation which allows for or is otherwise in favor of same-gender unions or marriages.
Legislation which prohibits or is otherwise against same-gender unions or marriages.
Any of various laws related to marriages of LGBTQIA+ persons.
Any of various laws related to the marriages of transgender persons.
Any of various laws related to the marriages of gay persons.
